## ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core 8 Migration

### Key Breaking Changes

| Framework Pattern | Core Equivalent | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | **Removed** — no equivalent | Used `Thread.Abort` internally; doesn't exist in Core |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` | No `endResponse` param; flow control via return |
| `Response.Clear()` | Not needed | Response isn't shared/buffered the same way |
| `Response.AddHeader()` | `Response.Headers.Append()` | New API surface |
| `Response.Write()` | `return Content()` or write to `Response.Body` | Action results replace direct writes |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | **Delete it** | `Thread.Abort` is obsolete in .NET Core; never thrown |
| WebForms event handlers | MVC action methods | No page lifecycle in Core |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a FileResult — no Response.Clear/Write/End dance needed.
        // The framework handles Content-Disposition and streaming.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        // In Core, prefer [Authorize] over manual checks.
        // But if you need runtime logic:
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
            // Flow stops here — no Thread.Abort, no endResponse bool.
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // NOTE: Do NOT port the ThreadAbortException catch block.
        // Thread.Abort is not supported in .NET Core and will never fire.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. `Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(_, true)` — the #1 migration trap**
These called `Thread.Abort()` internally. In .NET Core, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. If migrated code still references it, you get runtime crashes, not compile errors.

**2. Don't catch `ThreadAbortException`**
Any `catch (ThreadAbortException)` blocks are dead code in Core. Remove them — they mask the real intent and confuse readers.

**3. Writing directly to `Response.Body` after `return`**
In Framework, code after `Response.Redirect` sometimes still ran. In Core, once you `return` an `IActionResult`, the pipeline owns the response. Writing to `Response.Body` after returning a result causes `InvalidOperationException: Response has already started`.

**4. Prefer `[Authorize]` over manual auth checks**
```csharp
[Authorize]
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult RedirectAction()
{
    // No need to check IsAuthenticated — middleware handles it
    // and redirects to the login page configured in Program.cs
}
```

**5. File downloads — don't manually set headers**
`Controller.File()` handles `Content-Disposition`, content length, and streaming. Manual header manipulation risks double-headers or missing values.

**6. Null-safety on `User.Identity`**
In Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` if no auth middleware ran. Always use `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`.
